.TH VGP 1 "User Commands"
.SH NAME
vgp \- Parse a Valgrind logfile and present in human readable form
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBvgp\fR [\fIOPTIONS\fR] <\fIFILE\fR>
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBvgp\fR parses a log file generated by Valgrind and creates a more human readable version. It will remove
extraneous info like PIDs and adresses. Optionally, it will list call stack, the source for the offending
C/C++/Rust/Fortran function, highlighting the line causing the issue. The listing includes the source file and
line number if debug information was included in the application binary. This is displayed in a format that 
program editors like VsCode can use to jump to the source line with a <control-mouse click> from the terminal.
For best results, compile your application with debug information enabled. Use the \fI-g\fR or \fI-g3\fR options
for gcc. It also is suggested that you compile your source files with the full pathname and run Valgrind with
the \fI--fullpath-after=string\fR option. This will enable \fBvgp\fR to find the source files even if they
reside in different directories.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
<\fIFILE\fR>
The path to the input file. This is a required argument.
.TP
.BR \-t
Display call stack trace
.TP
.BR \-s
Display function source code and line for reported errors
.TP
.BR \-l
Display summary possible memory leaks reported
.TP
.BR \-v
Verbose display including the summary possible memory leaks reported, function source code and line number, and call stack trace
.TP
.BR \-h
Display the usage and description of the options
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBvalgrind --leak-check=full --log-file=valgrind-out.txt --fullpath-after=string ./your_program\fR
Run Valgrind and generate a log file with full pathnames enabled.
.TP
\fBvgp valgrind_out.txt\fR
Processes the log file named "valgrind_out.txt" and output the results to stdout.
.TP
\fBvgp valgrind_out.txt > output.txt\fR
Processes the log file named "valgrind_out.txt" and redirect the output to a file named "output.txt".
